	doi = {10.1051/0004-6361/202243975},
	abstract = {We report the detection of GJ 3090 b (TOI-177.01), a mini-Neptune on a 2.9-day orbit transiting a bright ({\textless}i{\textgreater}K{\textless}i/{\textgreater} = 7.3 mag) M2 dwarf located at 22 pc. The planet was identified by the Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite and was confirmed with the High Accuracy Radial velocity Planet Searcher radial velocities. Seeing-limited photometry and speckle imaging rule out nearby eclipsing binaries. Additional transits were observed with the LCOGT, {\textless}i{\textgreater}Spitzer,{\textless}i/{\textgreater} and ExTrA telescopes. We characterise the star to have a mass of 0.519 ± 0.013 {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}⊙{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} and a radius of 0.516 ± 0.016 {\textless}i{\textgreater}R{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}⊙{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}. We modelled the transit light curves and radial velocity measurements and obtained a planetary mass of 3.34 ± 0.72 {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}E{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}, a radius of 2.13 ± 0.11 {\textless}i{\textgreater}R{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}E{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}, and a mean density of g cm{\textless}sup{\textgreater}−3{\textless}sup/{\textgreater}. The low density of the planet implies the presence of volatiles, and its radius and insolation place it immediately above the radius valley at the lower end of the mini-Neptune cluster. A coupled atmospheric and dynamical evolution analysis of the planet is inconsistent with a pure H–He atmosphere and favours a heavy mean molecular weight atmosphere. The transmission spectroscopy metric of means that GJ 3090 b is the second or third most favorable mini-Neptune after GJ 1214 b whose atmosphere may be characterised. At almost half the mass of GJ 1214 b, GJ 3090 b is an excellent probe of the edge of the transition between super-Earths and mini-Neptunes. We identify an additional signal in the radial velocity data that we attribute to a planet candidate with an orbital period of 13 days and a mass of {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}E{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}, whose transits are not detected.},
