	abstract = {Cool stars on the main sequence generate X-rays from coronal activity, powered by a convective dynamo. With increasing temperature, the convective envelope becomes smaller and X-ray emission fainter. We present Chandra/HRC-I observations of four single stars with early A spectral types. Only the coolest star of this sample, τ 3 Eri (T eff ≍ 8, 000 K), is detected with \${\textbackslash}mathrm\{log\}(\{L\}\_\{X\}/\{L\}\_\{{\textbackslash}mathrm\{bol\}\})=-7.6\$ while the three hotter stars (T eff ≥ 8, 000 K), namely δ Leo, β Leo, and ι Cen, remain undetected with upper limits \${\textbackslash}mathrm\{log\}(\{L\}\_\{X\}/\{L\}\_\{{\textbackslash}mathrm\{bol\}\}) -8.4\$ . The drop in X-ray emission thus occurs in a narrow range of effective temperatures around {\textasciitilde}8100 K and matches the drop of activity in the C III and O VI transition region lines.},
