	url = {http://arxiv.org/abs/2203.16959},
	abstract = {We report on the discovery of a bound exoplanetary microlensing event from a blind search of data gathered from Campaign 9 of the Kepler K2 mission (K2C9). K2-2016-BLG-0005Lb is a densely sampled, binary caustic-crossing microlensing event with caustic entry and exit points that are resolved in the K2C9 data, enabling the lens-source relative proper motion to be measured. We have fitted a binary microlens model to the K2 dataset, and to simultaneous observations from the Optical Gravitational Lensing Experiment (OGLE-IV), Canada-France-Hawaii Telescope (CFHT), Microlensing Observations in Astrophysics (MOA-2), the Korean Microlensing Telescope Network (KMTNet), and the United Kingdom InfraRed Telescope (UKIRT). Whilst the ground-based data only sparsely sample the binary caustic, they provide a clear detection of parallax that allows us to break completely the microlensing mass-position-velocity degeneracy and measure the planet's mass directly. We find a host mass of \$0.58{\textbackslash}pm0.03 {\textasciitilde}\{{\textbackslash}rm M\}\_{\textbackslash}odot\$ and a planetary mass of \$1.1 {\textbackslash}pm 0.1 {\textasciitilde}\{{\textbackslash}rm M\_J\}\$. The system lies at a distance of \$5.2 {\textbackslash}pm 0.2{\textasciitilde}\$kpc from Earth towards the Galactic bulge. The projected physical separation of the planet from its host is found to be \$4.2 {\textbackslash}pm 0.3{\textasciitilde}\$au which, for circular orbits, corresponds to \$a = 4.4{\textasciicircum}\{+1.9\}\_\{-0.4\}{\textasciitilde}\$au and period \$P = 13{\textasciicircum}\{+9\}\_\{-2\}{\textasciitilde}\$yr, making K2-2016-BLG-0005Lb a close Jupiter analogue. Though previous exoplanet microlensing events have included space-based data, this event is the first bound microlensing exoplanet to be discovered from space-based data. Even through a space telescope not designed for microlensing studies, this result highlights the advantages for exoplanet microlensing discovery that come from continuous, high-cadence temporal sampling that is possible from space. (Abridged).},
