asciicircum}\{-1\}\$, we estimate an increase in half-mass formation time from \${\textbackslash}sim\$0.5 Gyr to \${\textbackslash}sim\$1.2 Gyr from low- to high-\${\textbackslash}lambda\_\{{\textbackslash},R\_\{{\textbackslash}rm\{e\}\}\}{\textasciicircum}\{{\textbackslash}rm\{{\textbackslash},eo\}\}\$ galaxies. Slow rotators do not appear to fit these trends. Their residual \${\textbackslash}alpha\$-enhancement is indistinguishable from other galaxies with \${\textbackslash}lambda\_\{{\textbackslash},R\_\{{\textbackslash}rm\{e\}\}\}{\textasciicircum}\{{\textbackslash}rm\{{\textbackslash},eo\}\}{\textbackslash}lessapprox0.4\$, despite being both larger and more massive. This result shows that galaxies with \${\textbackslash}lambda\_\{{\textbackslash},R\_\{{\textbackslash}rm\{e\}\}\}{\textasciicircum}\{{\textbackslash}rm\{{\textbackslash},eo\}\}{\textbackslash}lessapprox0.4\$ experience a similar range of star formation histories, despite their different physical structure and angular momentum.},
