	abstract = {A model is presented to explain the observed frequency distribution of flare energies, based on independent flaring at a number of distinct topological structures (separators) within active-region magnetic fields. The model is a modification and generalization of a recent model due to Craig (2001), and reconciles that model with the observed flare waiting-time distribution, and the observed absence of a flare waiting-time versus energy relationship. The basic assumptions of the model are that flares of energy E∼\$\${\textbackslash}left( {\textbackslash}ell  {\textbackslash}right)\$\$2 occur at separators of length \$\${\textbackslash}left( {\textbackslash}ell  {\textbackslash}right)\$\$, and that the frequency of flaring at a separator is defined by the Alfvén transit time of the structure. To reproduce the observed distribution of flare energies the model requires a probability distribution P(\$\${\textbackslash}left( {\textbackslash}ell  {\textbackslash}right)\$\$)∼\$\${\textbackslash}left( {\textbackslash}ell  {\textbackslash}right)\$\$−1 of separator lengths \$\${\textbackslash}left( {\textbackslash}ell  {\textbackslash}right)\$\$within active regions. This prediction of the model is in principle testable. A theoretical origin for this distribution is also discussed.},
