	abstract = {We present an analysis of contemporaneous photospheric, chromospheric and coronal structures on the {\textless}P /{\textgreater}highly active K-dwarf star BO Mic (Speedy Mic). We concentrate on a moderate flare that we localize in the stellar {\textless}P /{\textgreater}atmosphere and study its energetics, size and thermal behavior. {\textless}P /{\textgreater}The analysis is based on strictly {\textless}P /{\textgreater}simultaneous X-ray, UV- and optical observations carried out by XMM-Newton and the VLT. {\textless}P /{\textgreater}We use Doppler imaging and related methods {\textless}P /{\textgreater}for the localization of features. {\textless}P /{\textgreater}Based on X-ray spectroscopy we study the {\textless}P /{\textgreater}the coronal plasma in and outside the flare. {\textless}P /{\textgreater}The flare emits in X-rays and UV, but is not detected in white light; {\textless}P /{\textgreater}it is located at intermediate latitude between an extended spot group and {\textless}P /{\textgreater}the weakly spotted pole. We estimate its height to be below 0.4 stellar radii, making it {\textless}P /{\textgreater}clearly distinct in longitude and height from the prominences found {\textless}P /{\textgreater}about two stellar radii above the surface. {\textless}P /{\textgreater}In contrast to BO Mic's photospheric brightness, {\textless}P /{\textgreater}neither its chromospheric nor its X-ray emission show a pronounced {\textless}P /{\textgreater}rotational modulation. {\textless}P /{\textgreater}Based on observations obtained at the ESO VLT Obs. No. 078.D-0865(A) and XMM-Newton Obs. Id. 0400460301 and 0400460401. Doppler imaging line profiles are only available in electronic form at http://www.aanda.org},
