	doi = {10.1093/pasj/56.5.813},
	abstract = {A report is made on the Chandra archival data analysis of NGC 2068, which is one of the nearest (∼ 400 pc) and X-ray active star-forming regions, with an estimated age of 105-6yr. The observation was made for 100ks. Using the wavdetect tool, 152 X-ray sources were detected, of which 52 had counterparts in the 2MASS survey. One of the brightest X-ray sources is apparently identified with a V = 10.42 late B-type main-sequence star, HD 38563S. During the observation, it exhibited two X-ray flares, with the 0.5-8.0keV luminosity reaching ∼ 1031.6 erg s-1. The flare X-rays evolved on a time scale of several hours, and showed a thermal spectrum of temperature of ∼ 5 keV. These results suggests that this star forms an active binary, although contamination by a T Tauri star also remains an alternative possibility.},
